ion -- tPerspectives on the future of Western capitalism -- t18 The double movement and the perspectives of contemporary capitalism -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince its emergence at the end of the seventeenth century, industrial capitalism as a specific form of social organisation has set recurrent challenges to its own persistence, and until today, it has proved to be successful to develop new ways of accumulation based on its capacity of adaptation. Is this process of transition now accelerating or reaching an end point? This book is a critical exploration of capitalism in transition, bringing together cutting edge, world renowned scholars who reflect from different disciplinary points of view. This collection engages with the primarily Western themes of welfare capitalism and social fragmentation. Structured over three parts, the book analyses; the transformations of welfare societies and capitalism with a focus on South European welfare states and their (in)capacity to tackle poverty; the transformation of work and migration with a special attention to informality and the question of social rights; and the transformation of cities.This book is relevant to United Nations Sustainable Development Goal 1, No poverty.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCapitalism. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh  aEnzo Mingione.  aFordist crisis.  aNo poverty.  aWestern capitalism.  acitizenship systems.  afinancial capital.  aglobal capitalism.  amigratory flows.  aneoliberal transformation.  anew employment regimes.  apostwar capitalism.  apoverty.  awelfare policies.1 aAndreotti, Alberta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAndreotti, Alberta, eeditor.4edt4http://